Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by (Azade Dehghanpour)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This Loan Data dataset from Prosper contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. Further elaboration on variables can be found at Prosper API Definition Page explains the .

Structure of Dataset¶

Dataset consist of 113,937 entries on loans borrowed through 'Prosper' peer-to-peer lending marketplace. Each entry (row) has 81 features (fields/columns) that describe certain attributes of the Borrower (Member), borrower's loan request(Listing), Lender(Investor), and the Loan itself.

Main Feature(s) of Interest in Dataset¶

Area of interest is the makeup of Prosper customers (Borrowers)in terms of the level of their income (income range and monthly income), available credit and credit grade.
Moreover, categories in which the members apply for loans (business, home improvement,...), size of the loan they usually borrow for the stated purpose and what repayment schedule they desire most ( 12,36 or 60 months) will be explored.
Finally, the exploration and analysis are to explain the relationship between certain features of members (monthly income, available credit, debt to income ratio) and Annual Percentage Rate(APR) they recieve.

Dataset Features Believed to Support Investigation into Feature(s) of Interest¶

Following features will be explored. However, if not a good fit for the purpose of this analysis, they might be discarded in later steps.

  • Borrower:

    • Member Key
    • Occupation
    • Income Range
    • Stated Monthly Income
    • Debt to Income Ratio
    • Available Bankcard Credit
    • Credit Grade

  • Loan:

    • Listing Key
    • Listing Category
    • Loan Number
    • Loan Original Amount
    • Total Prosper Loans
    • Term
    • Monthly Loan Payment

  • Borrowers Evaluation:

    • Prosper Rating
    • Borrower APR

Given that 85% of members fall into 4 categories ( \$25,000-100,000+ Income Range), in bivariant and multi-variantexploration the focus will be solely on these categories. However, it should be first investigated how much of the loans borrowed is attributed to them. It will be clarified later in the section of bivariant explorations.

Data for monthly income is spread over a considerably large range ( 0 1.75 million) while 75% of values fell under 7000 . Using the linear scale would show and drastically skewed distribution that would not represent the data accurately. To Solve this problem the data was scaled logarithmically(right) and on left distribution only shows the data for which monthly income alls under 30000.
Distribution of monthly income appears to be right skewed with Median at ~\$4500, majority have a monthly income between \\$3000-\$10,000

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Number of NaN values in entries for Credit Grade is significant. Any investigation and analysis on this feature will be approached with cautioun.

  • Out of 113066 entries, 3529 for Occupation are NaN values. And in 40% of the entries, it is not clear what the occupation is as the value is either 'Other' or 'Professional'. Therefore, Occupationwill not be used to categorize members.

  • 51% of loans are taken for Debt Consolidation. Unfortunately 25% of entries offer un-informative data stating 'Not Available' and 'Other' for Listing Category. It should be decided later on how to handle this issue.

  • Due to the number of outliers the distribution for Stated Monthly Income, Debt To Income Ratio and Available Bankcard Credi are significantly right skewed.

  • One sudden jump is observed in the distribution. It appears that most frequent APR falls roughly between 0.35 and 0.36

The data itself didn't need transformation. But scale transformation helped to better see the distribution across the range.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Data Cleaning:

  • Listing Category:
    • Numerical values were replace with their literal values.

Scale Transformation

  • StatedMonthlyIncome:

    • Data for monthly income is spread over a considerably large range ( 0 1.75 million) while 75% of values fell under 7000 . Using the linear scale would show and drastically skewed distribution that would not represent the data accurately. To solve this problem upper bound was set to 30000, and bin size was chosen as such to capture the range of values.

  • DebtToIncomeRatio

    • Entries for Debt to Income Ratio fall anywhere between 0%-1000% with increments as low as 0.1%). However, more than 90% of datapoint are under 100%. Therefore, limiting the selection of data point to those with a maximum ratio of 1 presents a better understanding of how the data is distributed. The distribution is right skewed with median at ~0.2 and 75% of values falling under ~0.35.
  • AvailableBankcardCredit
    • Given the broad range of entries for available credit (between 0 - 600,000+), log scaling proved to be the best way to ensure the distribution is depicted rather accurately.With Median at \$4000, Most members have less than \\$10000 credit available on their bank card and for 20% of member it stand under \$1000. There are outliers on both higher and lower ends and will be dealt with in later stages.

Income Range appeared to be viable feature based on which the data can be categorized and further explored. There are no NaN value and the categories are informative enough. However, categories such as'Not Displayed' does not offer much explanation and the categories $0' and \\$1-24,999. 85% of members fall into 4 categories ( \$25,000-49,999,\\$50,000-74,999, \$75,000-99,999, \\$100,000+). To ensure these for categories have enough share in the loans borrowed, in the next step, the distribution of loans(percentage of total amount) across categories of IncomeRange is explored. If the criteria of being a majory group is met, focus data will be data related to these four categories only.

Relationships among Features of Interest¶

Overall the relationships either positive or negative do not appear to be strong. But given the correlation coeficients, the following is observed in the data:

  • members with higher monthly incom and more credit available on their bank card, enjoy better APR and opt for larger loans.
  • As Debt to Income Ratio decreases APR improves. While the available credit on bank card does not make a strong impact on Debt to Income Ratio, it is observed that higher monthly income lowers the ratio.
  • Available credit contributes most to improving APR.

  • Although most members, as observed earliear, pay off their loans in 36months. It appears that , across all income range categories, 60month term is favored for repayment of higher loans.
  • Average amount of loans borrowed is higher for members with better credit rate
  • for the 3 highest income range category on average loans taken for debt consolidation is the largest while for members in 25000-49,999 income range larger average loan is borrowed for business.

What is observed in scatter plots is very much in line with earlier objervations. However, there are cases that data has behaved out of character. Such discrepencies should be attributed to the fact that the data available for Credit Grade is extremely limited. Therefore random entries and existance of outlier can lead to misleading representation of relationships

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Debt to Income Ration appears to be a deciding factor wether a member recieves an optimum APR. Monthly income and available credit further improve or worsen APR. However, the impact differ for different Credit Grades. While for members with good credit increse in monthly income does not contribute to better APR considerably and available credit is a more deciding contributor, for those with a rather low credit grade the increase in monthly income makes a visible impact on lowering APR.

Limitation¶

Listing Category A significant portion of loans are listed under other or Not available. Therefore the analysis falls short of accurately make a statement on what the loans are borrowed for.

Credit Grade For 85% of the entries this valuable indicator is not available. Though quite an important and interesting feature, lack of enough entries caused a degree of descrepency.
